Prime Number Theorem (Elementary Proof) ‚Äî Proof Forge Specification

Module Tag: PNT_Elementary
Zero-Type Class: Combinatorial_Zero, Additive_Zero, Inequality_Zero, Arithmetic_Zero
Domain: Elementary Number Theory / Additive Combinatorics
Objective: Encode the Erd≈ës‚ÄìSelberg elementary proof of the Prime Number Theorem using the Proof Forge F/E/S/R/C architecture ‚Äî without complex analysis.

‚∏ª

1. Problem Definition

Statement:
Let œÄ(x) be the number of primes ‚â§ x. Then:

\pi(x) \sim \frac{x}{\log x}
\quad \text{as } x \to \infty.

Equivalent through the Chebyshev function:

\psi(x) = \sum_{n \le x} \Lambda(n) \sim x.

Core Mechanism (Elementary Engine):
The central identity (Selberg Identity) provides a purely arithmetic relationship between primes and weighted sums of logarithms. It replaces spectral analysis with a combinatorial identity that couples \psi(x), \psi(x/n), and convolutions of \log:

\sum_{n \le x} \Lambda(n) \log\frac{x}{n} =
x\log x - x + O(\sqrt{x}) - \sum_{ab \le x} \Lambda(a)\Lambda(b).

This identity acts as the flow rule for the elementary proof.

‚∏ª

2. Flow Component: F_PNT_Elementary

Name: Iterative_Scale_Renormalization
Type: Discrete real-variable flow; renormalization across integer scales.

Flow Definition

Instead of evolving a function along a contour in ‚ÑÇ, the elementary approach evolves \psi(x) through:
	‚Ä¢	recursive application of Selberg‚Äôs identity,
	‚Ä¢	analysis of sums over divisors,
	‚Ä¢	decomposition of \psi(x) into contributions at multiple scales.

Flow Evolution

For decreasing scales:

x \rightarrow \frac{x}{2} \rightarrow \frac{x}{3} \rightarrow \cdots,

the flow enforces consistency across intervals through averaging and convolution.

This is a Renormalization Group flow on the arithmetic structure of primes.

Flow Goal

Use the recursive structure to propagate constraints on the average behavior of the error term:

\Delta(x) = \psi(x) - x.

‚∏ª

3. Energy Component: E_PNT_Elementary

Name: Positivity_Constraint_Functional
Type: Combinatorial Monotonicity Constraint.

Energy Specification

Selberg‚Äôs identity leads to expressions of the form:

E(x) = \sum_{n \le x} a_n^2 \ge 0,

where a_n is constructed from \Lambda(n) and finite differences of \psi.

Key Insight:
Any persistent deviation of \psi(x) above or below x yields:
	‚Ä¢	a contradiction with the positivity of E(x),
	‚Ä¢	because the squared term forces rigid inequalities that \Delta(x) cannot escape.

Energy Goals
	‚Ä¢	Trap \Delta(x) inside an asymptotically vanishing window.
	‚Ä¢	Guarantee \Delta(x)/x \to 0.
	‚Ä¢	Replace spectral monotonicity with positivity monotonicity.

Energy Behavior

This energy does not decay analytically ‚Äî
it decays arithmetically via the structure of convolution identities.

‚∏ª

4. Singularities Component: S_PNT_Elementary

Name: Hypothetical_Deviation_Regimes
Type: Additive-Combinatorial Obstructions.

Singularity Classification

Type	Description	Behavior
Good Singularity	\psi(x) \sim x	Compatible with the positivity energy.
Bad Singularity	\psi(x) > (1+\epsilon)x or \psi(x) < (1-\epsilon)x for infinitely many x	Violates positivity constraints when fed into the flow.

Analogy:
In the analytic PNT, singularities were zeros/poles.
Here, singularities are forbidden behavioral regimes of the error term.

Objective

Identify all patterns of \Delta(x) that, if allowed, would violate the combinatorial inequalities.

‚∏ª

5. Surgery Component: R_PNT_Elementary

Name: Contradiction_by_Inequality
Type: Combinatorial Surgery.

Mechanism
	1.	Assume a bad singularity regime:
\psi(x) > (1+\epsilon)x \quad \text{on a long interval}
or its negative counterpart.
	2.	Feed this assumption into the Selberg flow.
	3.	Compute the resulting energy expression E(x).
	4.	Show that the assumption forces E(x) to become negative ‚Äî
which is impossible.

Outcome of Surgery

The contradiction removes the hypothetical regime.
Only the ‚Äúgood‚Äù singularity behavior survives.

This is the arithmetic counterpart of:
	‚Ä¢	contour surgery (analytic PNT),
	‚Ä¢	topological forcing (PB theorem).

‚∏ª

6. Classification Component: C_PNT_Elementary

Name: Asymptotic_Prime_Distribution

Final Conclusion

After eliminating all incompatible regimes, the only stable classification is:

\psi(x) = x + o(x),

which yields:

\pi(x) \sim \frac{x}{\log x}.

The classification is forced by the positivity structure and recursive flow.

